Acanthostega gunnari lived between 380 and 360 million years ago when animals made the transition from the sea to land.

Scientists are fascinated by the species because it is thought to be crucial to understanding the anatomy and ecology of the earliest tetrapods.

However, after hundreds of millions of years buried in the ground, fossils are often damaged and deformed. 

